sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE INNINGS TAKE OVER TOP SPOT FOLLOWING THEIR VICTORY.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons made four for 38 on Friday to help Leicestershire beat Somerset by 39 runs in two days to take the county championship.

However, their stay at the top could be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey are closing in on victory while Kent are making up for lost time in their rain-affected match against Nottinghamshire.

Leicestershire, who dismissed Somerset for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, extended their first innings by 94 runs before being dismissed for 296 when England opener Andy Caddick took three for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset made a solid start to their second innings before Simmons came in and reduced them to 174.
However, Essex are certain to regain top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such helped them win their game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, seen as England's one-day surplus, hit 158, his first championship century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
Towards the close Yorkshire had turned that into a 37-run advantage but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes with four for 24 off 48 balls, leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.
At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another name abandoned by England, continued to silence his critics with four for 80 in Friday's match against Warwickshire after his four for 45 on Thursday.
England hopes were well supported by Mark Butcher who made 70 as Surrey closed on 429 for seven, 234 all out.
Derbyshire continued their hunt for a first title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for 5 in their second innings and are still 100 runs away from avoiding a one-wicket defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody hit a six on 82 but Chris Adams hit 123 and Tim O'Gorman 109 to take Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the disappointment of the opening day of their match being badly affected by the weather, Kent geared up to leave Nottinghamshire on 214.
Paul Johnson's brave 84 kept them afloat but former English fast bowler Martin McCague made four for 55.
With the stumps, Kent had reached 108 on three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED AS ENGLAND CAPTAIN.
Alan Shearer, the world's most expensive footballer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams and former captain David Platt, who were in charge during the European Championship in June.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer took the captaincy on a trial basis but new manager Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take on the role.
"I'm sure there won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could do the job, but when I spoke to Alan, he was up for it and really wanted it.
"It is very difficult to come to a 100 per cent conclusion on such a matter in four days...
But he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team's situation despite playing in front. "
Teddy Sheringham, Shearer's goalscoring partner at Euro 96, withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He will probably be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle team-mate Les Ferdinand.
FOOTBALL - ROMANIA DEFEATED LITHUANIA IN THE UNDER-21 MATCH.
Romania defeated Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 at half-time) in a European Under-21 football match on Friday.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS STAY OFF THE STREETS AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd will have to play their next home match behind closed doors after their fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home defeat that ended Rotor's short-lived league lead.
Anatoly Gorokhovsky, Chairman of the Russian League Disciplinary Committee, said on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on 3 September.
The club, which excluded Manchester United from the UEFA Cup last year, was fined 1,000 dollars.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position ahead of the 11 matches to be played in the championship.
The Volgograd side, three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, have one game in hand on the leaders and two games in hand on the Moscow team.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran steps into the ring on Saturday in another age-defying attempt to continue his long career.
Duran, 45, will face little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in a super middleweight title fight in Panama City.
The bout, Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is being billed as "The Return of the Legend" and Duran is still talking like he was in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
Speaking to Reuters, Duran said, "I am not retiring.

However, those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who won titles in four different weight divisions - lightweight, middleweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he's on the cutting edge of his career.
"If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the greatest boxers in the world," said Ramon Manzanares, president of the Panama Boxing Association.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes to win the 10-rounder to set up a rematch with Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho won a controversial points decision over the Panamanian in their title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO AND O'BRIEN DOUBLE SADNESS UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday but Wimbledon finalists MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of upsets at the US Open.
The 11th seed Washington was unable to repeat his miraculous comeback at Wimbledon, losing 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 to Alex O'Brien in a battle that lasted two hours and 51 minutes on the Stadium court.
In the side grandstand, No. 10 seed Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection, bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The grumpy left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme was uneventful, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to dig himself out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole by winning 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to beginners.
Coming back from two sets down at 1-5 down in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-final, Washington looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington returned.
"I kept telling myself, 'keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who finished 65th.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself for that - normally I would have folded up the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former U.S. collegiate national champion, hit 17 aces to subdue Washington, which never gave up.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, and after Washington saved a break point with a forehand winner, he broke O'Brien 4-2 with a backhand winner.
The Texan scored two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted her eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and try to move him a little bit.
I think he got a little tense at some moments," Washington said. "
But I think it served quite well when it was needed. "

Tarango, who was fined $ 28,000 for a tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago and suspended from the tournament at the All-England Club this year, argued and taunted fans during a two-hour and 24-minute live tango with Rios in the stands.
An enthusiastic cheering section supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American who was the centre of attention.
"I'm an emotional player," says Tarango in 104th place. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused."
The match ended in a tiebreaker in the third set, with the American player winning 7-5, much to the horror of the spectators.
"I love the crowd, even though they boo me every day.
It fuels me and allows me to play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played my best tennis in college, with fraternities throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He always complains too much," said Rios. "
I think I played very badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were travelling too fast.
I've lost more points than I've ever lost.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play an American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sent mocking kisses to the crowd and then shook his body in a mocking salute to a group supporting Rios.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said about the fans. "
At the same time, they're openly cheering against me.
I thought I'd give them a bit of glamour after I won."
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading rusher at quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever play under centre, retired Thursday.
Cunningham spent his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham, a three-time Pro Bowl selection, rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the great fans of Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I am sad to leave, I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
Randall has been a cornerstone of the Eagles during his 11 years in Philadelphia, providing many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Selected in the second round in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 per cent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham's already signed on as broadcaster.
